 understand blackness, indigeneity, and the animal; analyzes Charles Burnett’s films as commentaries on the place of animals in Black life; and shows how equestrian novels address Black and animal life in ways that rehearse the practices of the slavocracy. By focusing on doing rather than being, Holland demonstrates that Black life is not solely likened to animal life; it is relational and world-forming with animal lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericanszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aFeminist theory. 0aHuman-animal relationshipszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aHuman-animal relationships. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Black Studies (Global).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027065?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027065423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027065/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles